06487nam a22008295i 9780292798434DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212004txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927984347 a10.7560/7024862doi  a(DE-B1597)588467  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 4aQH104.5.G68W48 2004 7aNAT0110002bisacsh04a577.68/097922200aWetland and Riparian Areas of the Intermountain West :bEcology and Management /ced. by Mark C. McKinstry, Stanley H. Anderson, Wayne A. Hubert. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2004  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Laws and Regulations Pertaining to Wetland Areas in the Intermountain West -- t2. Variation in Hydrology, Soils, and Vegetation of Natural Palustrine Wetlands among Geologic Provinces -- t3. Ecological Processes of Riverine Wetland Habitats -- t4. Wildlife Use of Riverine Wetland Habitats -- t5. Management of Riverine Wetland Habitats -- t6. Irrigation, Salinity, and Landscape Patterns of Natural Palustrine Wetlands -- t7. Wildlife of Natural Palustrine Wetlands -- t8. Management of Natural Palustrine Wetlands -- t9. Components, Processes, and Design of Created Palustrine Wetlands -- t10. Wildlife of Created Palustrine Wetlands -- t11. Management of Created Palustrine Wetlands -- t12. Classification, Assessment, Monitoring, and Evaluation of Riverine and Palustrine Wetland Ecosystems -- tConclusions and Future Directions -- tAppendix -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWetlands and riparian areas between the Rocky Mountains and the Sierra Nevada are incredibly diverse and valuable habitats. More than 80 percent of the wildlife species in this intermountain region depend on these wetlands—which account for less than 2 percent of the land area—for their survival. At the same time, the wetlands also serve the water needs of ranchers and farmers, recreationists, vacation communities, and cities. It is no exaggeration to call water the "liquid gold" of the West, and the burgeoning human demands on this scarce resource make it imperative to understand and properly manage the wetlands and riverine areas of the Intermountain West. This book offers land managers, biologists, and research scientists a state-of-the-art survey of the ecology and management practices of wetland and riparian areas in the Intermountain West. Twelve articles examine such diverse issues as laws and regulations affecting these habitats, the unique physiographic features of the region, the importance of wetlands and riparian areas to fish, wildlife, and livestock, the ecological function of these areas, their value to humans, and the methods to evaluate these habitats. The authors also address the human impacts on the land from urban and suburban development, mining, grazing, energy extraction, recreation, water diversions, and timber harvesting and suggest ways to mitigate such impacts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aAdamus, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Stanley H., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBozek, Michael A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEhrhart, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGammonley, James H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Paul L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHart, E. Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuber